---
import ReportLayout from "../../../layouts/ReportLayout.astro";
import Section from "../../../components/Section.astro";
import { chapterHref, chapterNavItems } from "../../../lib/chapters";
import { chrome, localePath } from "../../../lib/i18n";

const locale = "en" as const;
const nav = chapterNavItems(locale);
const t = chrome(locale);
const selfHref = localePath(locale, "guides/security-privacy");
const ch01 = chapterHref("01-log-is-the-runtime", locale);
---

<ReportLayout
  title="Trust, privacy & SECURITY · Agent Atelier"
  description="Maka trust model: OS-account boundary, WorkspacePrivacyContext, Seatbelt honesty, and report scope — a companion report, not a seventh worldview chapter."
  nav={nav}
  activeHref={selfHref}
  locale={locale}
>
  <article class="report">
    <header class="masthead">
      <p class="masthead__eyebrow">Companion guide · Specimen: maka-agent · {t.doneLabel}</p>
      <h1>
        <span class="masthead__title-zh">Trust, privacy &amp; SECURITY</span>
        <span class="masthead__title-en">Workspace privacy contract</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="masthead__sub">
        Teaching expansion of root <code>SECURITY.md</code> and
        <code>docs/workspace-privacy-context.md</code>: which layer is load-bearing, which is a UX
        safety net, and how privacy context fails closed. Orthogonal to §01–§06 — enter from
        <a href={`${ch01}#trust`}>§01 · #trust</a> /
        <a href={`${ch01}#sandbox`}>#sandbox</a> /
        <a href={`${ch01}#permission`}>#permission</a>, then read here.
      </p>
      <div class="masthead__meta">
        <span>Home · /guides/security-privacy</span>
        <span>Research · #59</span>
        <span>
          <a href={localePath("zh", "guides/security-privacy")}>中文</a>
        </span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <Section
      id="scene"
      label="Trust · Scene"
      title="Why an honest trust model"
      lede="Calling PermissionEngine a sandbox is more dangerous than shipping no screen — it teaches the wrong threat story."
    >
      <p>
        Maka is a single-tenant personal desktop assistant; tools run as the user’s OS identity. The
        only enforcement boundary against an adversarial LLM is the operating system. In-process
        screens (permission modes, output redaction, URL allowlists, WebSearch fail-closed) are
        valuable heuristics on attacker-influenced strings. When authorities conflict,
        <strong>code + contract tests win</strong>. This page tracks <code>SECURITY.md</code> — no
        security theater.
      </p>
      <blockquote class="pull">
        The only enforcement boundary against an adversarial LLM is the operating system.
      </blockquote>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="os-boundary"
      label="Trust · OS"
      title="Sole load-bearing boundary: the OS user account"
      lede="Tools inherit the user’s filesystem, network, and OS-permission envelope."
    >
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          <strong>OS user account</strong> — running non-admin is a user-side expectation, not
          in-product containment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>credentials.json</strong> — versioned plaintext JSON; dir 0o700 / file 0o600;
          atomic writes; no symlink/traversal escape. One authority for Desktop / TUI / headless.
          Electron safeStorage is no longer part of the boundary (#1125 one-shot import then delete).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Renderer ↔ Main</strong> — preload IPC is the trust boundary; semi-trusted
          renderer may read masked data; <strong>cleartext secrets never flow main→renderer</strong>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Settings masking</strong> — <code>••••••</code> means keep; empty string means
          explicit clear (including the Tavily key).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="heuristics"
      label="Trust · Heuristics"
      title="In-process screens are UX safety nets"
      lede="Useful; not containment guarantees."
    >
      <p>
        PermissionEngine (<code>PERMISSION_MODES</code> / <code>TOOL_CATEGORIES</code> /
        <code>PERMISSION_POLICY</code>), output redaction, URL allowlists, query normalization, and
        the WebSearch fail-closed chain are heuristics. Reports that only show their limits belong
        as <strong>ordinary issues</strong> unless an OS-boundary in §2 is also crossed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Mechanism teaching for permission and sandbox lives in
        <a href={`${ch01}#permission`}>§01 · #permission</a> /
        <a href={`${ch01}#sandbox`}>#sandbox</a>; this page only pins threat-model placement.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="seatbelt-honesty"
      label="Trust · Seatbelt"
      title="Seatbelt in code ≠ product boundary delivered"
      lede="Keep “mechanism ready” separate from “boundary shipped”."
    >
      <p>
        Runtime exposes a macOS Seatbelt (and Linux bubblewrap) command transformer, but current
        product compositions do <strong>not</strong> yet route command execution through it — so
        <code>SECURITY.md</code> §2.2 states it is <strong>not</strong> a product boundary today.
        Externally isolated runtimes may supply their own. See the sandbox README and §01
        <code>#sandbox</code>.
      </p>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="privacy-context"
      label="Trust · Privacy"
      title="WorkspacePrivacyContext: deliberately tiny"
      lede="Main owns the effective state; renderers must not self-attest."
    >
      <pre class="code-block" aria-label="WorkspacePrivacyContext">interface WorkspacePrivacyContext &#123;
  incognitoActive: boolean;
&#125;</pre>
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li>
          Authority path: settings UI requests change → main
          <code>getWorkspacePrivacyContext()</code> resolves → consumers receive the resolved
          context.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>validateWorkspacePrivacyContext()</code> rejects malformed input; it
          <strong>never</strong> defaults missing/invalid data to <code>false</code>. Unresolvable
          authoritative context → fail closed.
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>defaultWorkspacePrivacyContext()</code> is for explicit initialization only — not
          “guess allow”.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="consumer-rule"
      label="Trust · Consumers"
      title="false ≠ blanket allow"
      lede="Incognito did not block ≠ general permission to read, write, search, or transmit."
    >
      <p>
        <code>incognitoActive: false</code> only means incognito mode did not block the operation.
        Every privacy-sensitive consumer still applies its own settings, permission, and retention
        rules. When <code>incognitoActive</code> is true, consumers fail closed at their existing
        main-process boundary.
      </p>
      <p>
        Current inventory (owned by composition + tests; do not freeze the list in prose): WebSearch,
        thread search, local memory, plan reminders, automation can-fire, memory write validator. Do
        not invent a parallel incognito flag or let a renderer self-attest.
      </p>
      <aside class="history-aside">
        <p class="history-aside__tag">Verification</p>
        <p>
          <code>packages/core/src/incognito.ts</code> ·
          <code>apps/desktop/src/main/main.ts</code> (<code>getWorkspacePrivacyContext</code>) ·
          tests <code>incognito.test.ts</code> / <code>thread-search.test.ts</code> /
          <code>web-search-boundary.test.ts</code> / <code>local-memory-service.test.ts</code> /
          <code>memory.test.ts</code>.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="report-scope"
      label="Trust · Report"
      title="Report scope: in-scope vs ordinary issues"
      lede="Read SECURITY §2–§3 before choosing a private channel."
    >
      <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Report scope" tabindex="0">
        <table class="proto-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Situation</th>
              <th scope="col">Channel</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Crosses OS / credentials / IPC cleartext / masking boundary</td>
              <td>Private: security@maka.app (or private advisory)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Limits of PermissionEngine / redact / allowlist heuristics</td>
              <td>Ordinary issue / PR (out-of-scope as security)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Malformed privacy context treated as allow</td>
              <td>In-scope contract defect (must fail closed)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Marketing unwired Seatbelt as “sandboxed”</td>
              <td>Docs/product honesty; mechanism in #sandbox</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </Section>

    <Section
      id="honesty"
      label="Trust · Trilogy"
      title="Three honest docs, three jobs"
      lede="Do not treat threat-model archives as Current."
    >
      <ul class="plain-list">
        <li><code>SECURITY.md</code> — trust model + report scope</li>
        <li><code>docs/workspace-privacy-context.md</code> — tiny privacy contract</li>
        <li><code>packages/runtime/src/sandbox/README.md</code> — platform transform Current</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Threat-model archives (memory/search/voice) are history-only (#60); Current is code + the
        table above. Outline:
        <code>docs/research/trust-privacy-security-deep-outline.md</code>.
      </p>
    </Section>
  </article>
</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .pull {
    margin: 1.1rem 0 0;
    padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--softer);
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    max-width: 38em;
  }
  .plain-list {
    margin: 0.75rem 0 1.1rem;
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
    max-width: 42em;
  }
  .plain-list li {
    margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
  }
  .code-block {
    margin: 1rem 0 1.25rem;
    padding: 0.9rem 1.05rem;
    background: var(--soft);
    border: 1px solid var(--hair);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    overflow-x: auto;
    max-width: 42em;
    white-space: pre;
  }
  .table-wrap {
    margin: 1rem 0 1.25rem;
    max-width: 46em;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }
  .proto-table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }
  .proto-table th,
  .proto-table td {
    border: 1px solid var(--hair);
    padding: 0.45rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: left;
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  .proto-table thead th {
    background: var(--soft);
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .history-aside {
    margin: 1.25rem 0 0;
    padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--hair);
    background: var(--softer);
    max-width: 42em;
  }
  .history-aside__tag {
    margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
  }
  .history-aside p {
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
